poem:
The Sizzleghast and the Heat‑Set Feed

When kettle-tide the workshop hummed,
The dunkle-therm was caution-set;
Ebonite feeds in nightglass numbed,
For ebonite feed heat‑set, yet.

Take heed, nibling, mind the flare now;
The Sizzleghast goes sss—so sly;
Keep distance, keep your patient brow;
It singes shoplings by and by.

He fetched the kettle, mild and clean;
A pinch of steam, a snug-fit kit;
Ebonite feed and nib between
To coax the coupling snugly fit.

He waited by the simmer-sill;
Hushish the workshop went to hush;
When Sizzleghast slid, limb and will,
Tss-ssss and crackle-crackle, hush!

He braced the jig; he bent with care;
Clack-snug the nib and feed did meet;
He kissed the heat with cloth and air;
Sss-pop! the Sizzleghast lost its seat.

The inkwell purled; the lines ran sound;
He lifted pen in light reset;
Through paper-plain it whirred and bound;
Ebonite feed in warm reset.

Back ran the boy to Bench-Old One;
He waved the pen—slick, straight, and set;
Quill-keeper grinned: “Well writ, well done!”
“Your ebonite feed is heat‑set.”

When kettle-tide the workshop hums,
The simmer-lamps are meekly set;
Bright ebonfeeds in ink run drums,
And all is heat‑set proper set.

Lead Type in a Composing Stick

At letterdusk the leadlings lay,
click-clacking in composing stick;
the picas pale in quoined array,
while glimmercases briskly tick.

Take heed, apprentice: guard your thumbs;
the Kerningwyrm craves pressroom flesh;
it hisses through the forme and hums,
its ink-lashed spit shall thee enmesh.

I gauged my stick to one em wide,
with guttergloves and pica-pins;
I lipped each slug and snugged beside,
till, at the crink, the quoins gave grins.

Through casescape the Kerningwyrm
came sizzle-sly with jellied breath;
its ligature-lapping squirm
made makereadies gasp of death.

I raised my stick, chaseling-blade;
click-click went sorts; the gutters sang;
I kneed the quire; the quoins obeyed,
skreek! skrrk!—then leadlings loudly clang!

I pinched its tail in chock and chase,
I snapped its beak with measure true;
through em and en I drove the case,
chk-CHK! the kerning cracked in two.

Back to the stone I steady-stepped,
with proof-slip, pelt, and letter-lore;
the foreman winked; the formes were kept,
and sang old shopfloor lore once more.

At letterdawn the leadlings lay,
click-clacking in composing stick;
the picas bright in quoined array,
and glimmercases softly tick.

Parting-Song at Platform Side

It chimed the clocks; the whistles whined;
the steamish dodos dribbed and drew;
all baggly were the browse-of-mind;
and muffle-moths went coo-choo-choo.

Heed, child, the Lingerloon, my sprout;
whose tut-tut teeth and ticket-tags;
it gulps your Bye with binding doubt,
and drags it near the buffer-brags.

I took my ticket-snip in hand;
my snugfare coat I buttoned through;
I practised, poised upon the stand,
a brisk good-journey, clear and true.

I perched beside the signal-post;
the hushful steam went sibil-sigh;
the lamps lit up like waiting-ghost;
and weary clocks clicked “why, oh, why.”

Down sidle-crept the Lingerloon;
its sigh-strings strummed a drawly tone;
and loomed along the sidetrack moon;
it crooned a drag-a-drowsy drone.

I snapped my ticket-snip to guard;
click-clack! the punch-teeth piped and pecked;
I stepped within the parting-yard;
chik-chak! its clambered loops I checked.

I spoke the clean and final “Go.”
ker-ching! the clocks chimed choo-by-choo;
the Lingerloon let loose: “go, go!”
and dwindled down to whisper-coo.

Back, back I strode, past parcel-stacks;
my elder clapped the breezy air;
“O best of brinks and bramble-tracks!”
“Huroo! your heart held light and fair!”

It chimed the clocks; the whistles whined;
the steamish dodos dribbled through;
all baggly stayed the browse-of-mind;
and muffle-moths cried coo-choo-choo.

The Spaghettigon

It bleeped o'clock; the noodle-snakes
Went whurl and weeble round the rig;
All squelchy swam the filter-lakes,
And buzzle droned the dronelings big.

Beware the Cablokraken, child;
Its sizzle-lure is wow-and-flay;
The Patchwyrm coils the meek and wild;
Keep steady hands or drift astray.

He donned his sonic-helm and plugs;
Tuned vactrol moons to humbly glow;
He kissed the clickclock, purged the bugs;
And mapped his patchplan, row by row.

He perched beside the Thrumdrum rack;
The LFO sang whoop-and-weep;
The slew-tree swayed; the cables clack;
Click-tick the clock, then bleat-and-beep.

Through patch-brume crept Spaghettigon;
Its hiss was swerve and gnarl and squaw;
With wobblejaws and blinking on,
Ka-kzzzt it came with noodle-draw.

He gripped his clipper, blinked to score;
He yanked the ring of mute-and-make;
Three snips—shk-shk!—through tangle's roar,
And sliced the squizzy serpent-break.

He stood, the rig now neat and clear;
The Cablokraken lulled to loop;
O clicksome hour! Hurray, my dear!
They danced a bleep-bloop victor-whoop.

It bleeped o'clock; the noodle-snakes
Lay coiled and kind around the rig;
All silken were the filter-lakes,
And hushly hummed the dronelings big.

The Loomshuttlepick

In gloamish halls the warplets played,
They skein and skirl along the wick;
All whatsel threads were willow-swayed,
And loomed the dread Loomshuttlepick.

“Beware that shuttle-snarling maw,
The pick that pecks with clitter-click;
Beware the heddle-hag of straw,
The warpwyrm’s whirr and thrum-tik-tik.”

He took his weftwise weirblade keen,
A loomstick-lance of alder brown;
He buckled bobbin-bracts between,
And paced the purling picker-town.

He stood by spindle-brook to brood;
Hush—factory moons hung sickly;
He heard the creak in carding wood,
He sniffed the oil; it pooled sickly.

And, flutter-furling, out it slid—
The Loomshuttlepick, weftsprite drake;
Its teeth like tines that gritted grid,
Its shuttle tail went click-a-click.

Whirr-ware! it wove a snarl of night;
He leapt with loomstick’s levee flick;
Criss-cross he cleft the knotty blight,
Chak-chak the monster’s picker nicked.

Back threading through the thunder-mill,
He bore its husk on shuttle-stick;
O mum, O master, measure still,
He’s tamed the dread Loomshuttlepick!

In gloamish halls the warplets played,
They skein and skirl along the wick;
All whatsel threads were willow-swayed,
And loomed the dread Loomshuttlepick.

The Blued-Screw in the Movement

In mainspring dusk the cogs did croon,
and oilmist swam the hollow case;
the ticktide trolled a brassy tune;
through pivot-woods I found my place.

He said: "Beware the Blued-Screw's bite;
its temper blazes cold and true;
it nests where train and tremor fight,
deep in the heart of movement's blue."

I honed my turnspike, thin and neat;
click-tack, the bench did nod and nod;
I wore a glove of felted heat,
and prayed the gears-to-god of rod.

Past balance-loom and escapette,
through pinion-pines I slid with care;
the second-hand, a silver net,
kept sweeping ghosts from copper air.

Then skreek! the Blued-Screw showed its thread;
a spiral glare, a tempered grin;
it wormed the plate with cobalt dread,
and sang: tik-tok, come turn me in.

I set the slot; my turnspike flew—
krick-krack! through thread and tempered bone;
one smoothing twist, one breath of blue,
and silence oiled the rattling zone.

Back down the train I trod, at peace,
the ticktide bright, the hands near noon;
the elder's grin unlatched release,
and oilmist danced inside the lune.

In mainspring dusk the cogs still croon,
and hollow case holds gentle grace;
the ticktide hums a mended tune—
through pivot-woods I keep my place.

Fishtail Gouge Sweep

When sawdust dusk went suther-slight,
the clampjaws dozed in amber keep;
the bench-dogs blinked by lampful light,
and fishtail gouge lay soft in sweep.

Mind Knotterwight and Splinterwyrm;
they gnash the grain and gnurl the deep;
Shun Squeech-hoot in the varnish berm;
and guard thy hand and gouge and sweep!

He donned his smackled smock and hood;
He honed the fishtail, sweep of twelve;
The oilstone sang as edges stood;
He planned a path the knots would delve.

He stalked the sapwood lanes alone;
The Squee-hinge creaked and raspers peeped;
When Knotterwight with clicky bone
came hrowling out of burl and deep.

It swizzled spit; its whiskers skreel;
its knotgnash jaws went clack-a-cleep;
He set his stance from heel to heel,
and raised the gouge in crescent sweep.

Whish-whush it swept; a skirl of shave;
the fishtail flashed in whorled arrears;
He scarped the snarl from snarling stave,
ka-CHAK! ka-CHAK! it sheared its ears.

The Knotterwight unspooled its hide;
its glimmer-gleam went wilt and weep;
He pegged its heart of twisted pride,
and cleaved the knot to quiet sleep.

He strode back through the sapling hum;
his smock a snow of shiver-skeep;
"Ho home!" he cried, "the Wight is dumb!"
They hugged amid the curls knee-deep.

As sawdust dusk went suther-slight,
the clampjaws purred in amber keep;
the benchdogs blinked in mellow light,
and fishtail gouge returned to sweep.

The Keyclack

Morse straight key click—awake, O wires!
Through tick-tack nights of nickel bars;
The clattermorse through coilwood fires,
Dit-dah, dit-dah, on brassbound bars.

Beware the Tappalisk, my child,
The Dahgrim Dash that bites the tone;
Its keyfangs nick the cable wild,
And shun the Clickershrike alone.

He gripped his tapblade, tempered true;
He donned his mufflemitt of felt;
Through coilgrove lanes the signal blew,
And hush-hooded his jitternelt.

By ticklegraph in coilwood steeps
It heaved—a Tappalisk of black;
Dit-dit! Dah-dah! its keyclaws clack;
It skirled through wires and woken steeps.

He sent the countercode, so keen;
A keystrike carved between the sheen;
Tick-tock! the Tappalisk was split;
Dashblood was dripping; keyclaws slit.

He lugged the hushed husk home at dusk;
His elder grinned in copper light;
O brassbound joy! O nickel musk!
They stamped the floor in click-delight.

Morse straight key click—awake, O wires!
Yet keep your tick-tack watch and bars;
For clattermorse still prowls the fires,
Dit-dah, dit-dah—on brassbound bars.

Orin Bell Hum

At orrin-bell of gloaming's rim,
the woldlings flisk and vrum;
All pillowy the hedgerows swim,
and Orin Bell goes hum.

O child, take heed Orinbell Hum;
its thrimble-drone grows numb;
Shun snicker-sparks that gummy-drum;
and guard your thinking thumb.

I took my ringedge tinkerbrand;
its clink went cling-clang-klum;
I donned the glimmershade and band,
to hunt the Bellish Hum.

By drumble-pine I bide a while;
the hush went thrum-thrum-thrum;
Through mistle-murk the moonlet's smile,
the night made nethersome.

Hark! from the fen a wavvered tread,
a whumm and shimmer-sum;
The Orinbell Hum, bell-headed,
came flitter-flare to come.

Its knell-eyes knurled with copper glare;
its tongue beat dum-dum-dum;
With chime-feathered flank and wire-hair,
it thringled through the scum.

I sprang; my tinkerbrand sang bright;
skreek-skrang! the bellnotes spun;
I crosscut once, I cleft it right,
the humfell-thing was done.

Back lilt I home by drumble-pine;
my heart went ping-pang-plum;
They cried, "O brave of ring and tine!"
You hushed Orinbell Hum.

At orrin-bell, on gloaming's rim,
the woldlings flisk and vrum;
All pillowy the hedges dim,
and Orin Bell goes hum.

Ballad of the Nibgnasher

By nib and tine and micro‑mesh,
the scribble‑winds went swish‑swish‑swish;
Inkgrasses bowed in feather‑fresh,
while blot‑birds coughed a blup‑blip wish.

"Take heed," said Gram, "of gnash and gash;
that scripple‑thing of rasp and grind;
The Nibgnasher will nick and slash;
keep all your tines from yaw and wind."

I trued my tip with mesh‑pad fine,
and stropped the scribe‑edge slow and sure;
I flexed the lamplight down the line,
to see the spring of flow run pure.

My sworple‑steel was cusp and keen;
the cap‑snap sang klick‑lack‑klick‑lack;
I packed a pad of velvet‑green,
and sipped the dusk for rumor‑track.

Then from the margin‑thicket, hiss—
a Scrivervine went skree‑skra‑skraw;
and up the ruled‑bank, black as bliss,
the Nibgnasher uncurled its maw.

Its grin was grit and scratch‑spark snow;
its whiskers wick’d with inkspume sleet;
it chitter‑chattered, groh‑groh‑groh;
and rasped its hunger down the sheet.

I pitched the quiver‑quillon straight,
and tuned each tine to tingle‑true;
then sweep‑swept mesh in figure‑eight—
skritch‑skree! the gnash was notched in two.

It puddled pale and quiet‑curled;
the margin‑thicket breathed once more;
I capped the night and crossed the world,
through paper‑paths to Gram’s old door.

She tapped the kettle: plip‑plip‑plop;
"You’ve polished storms to scribble‑rain;
but mind the Quillquake, never stop
and keep your tinework in the grain."

By nib and tine and micro‑mesh,
the scribble‑winds go swish‑swish‑swish;
my page is calm and feather‑fresh,
and hush‑birds hum a blup‑blip wish.

Tinroof Thrumble

It drimbled dusk; the tinroof thrummed,
And plinkerskree the raindrops ran;
All clinkersheen the gutters hummed,
While patter-winds went flit-a-flan.

“Take heed,” quoth Gran, “the Rattlewrack;
That cladder-thing of tinny proof;
It gnashes nails and springs the tack;
Steer clear beneath the ringing roof.”

I grasped my clinkerspike by haft,
My drumblebuckler cinched on tight;
With eaves-keen ear I timed the draft,
And waited out the thrumble-night.

Ping-pling! the pit-pat pealed and pealed,
Skree-skrung! the gutters gargled froth;
Up shinned the Rattlewrack, tin-heeled,
Through rivet-rain and thunder-moth.

Its shimble-jaws went chitter-chack,
Its bolthead eyes were brassy blue;
It sniffled sparks along the track,
And clanged, “Tin-tender, I want you.”

Clink-clank my clinkerspike let fall,
Whirr-whet it whistled, keen and clean;
The Rattlewrack un-rattled all,
And shuddered flat in rainy sheen.

I heel-hopped home through pinging pools,
Its screwcap crown upon my hook;
“Well done,” quoth Gran, “you kept the rules:
Now set it by the chimney-nook.”

It drimbles dawn; the tinroof hums,
With plinkerskree yet soft and wan;
No Rattlewrack through rivet-rooms,
Just patter-winds that flit-a-flan.

The Kiridashi Scribe-Line

At gloam the boardlings brimmed and bent,
By sawdust-silver light;
The grainlings grooved, the knots were rent,
And shivs went sprickling bright.

Take heed the Scribeclaw, little one;
Its skreek will shear your mind;
Beware the Skewgrain's twisty run,
And Driftknot's snarl behind.

He gripped his kiridashi keen,
With bevel bright as brine;
He stroked the stock to summon clean
A faithful scribe-line fine.

He paced beside the benchbeam bole,
In hush of shop's slow hum;
Through shaving-drift his musing strolled,
Skree, skree—the whetstones drum.

Out slid the Scribeclaw, line-true lean,
A rasping, razored wraith;
Its inchworm edge went click and sheen,
With skritchling, skreel of scaith.

The kiridashi kissed the mark—
Skrick-crack through skurl and spine;
He cleft the creep with lantern-spark,
And sealed the scribe-line fine.

Huzzah! the Scribeclaw slumps to dust,
Its skreek a shrinking thread;
Home strode he, edge in oiled-up trust;
The curls lay quiet, spread.

At gloam the boardlings breathed and bent,
By sawdust-argent light;
No Skewgrain skulked, the knots were spent,
And shivs lay sprickled bright.
